data.enText: an award that is given to a person who wins a competition, race, etc. or who does very good work
She was awarded the Nobel Peace prize.

data.chText: 他获得木管乐器组一等奖。
data.enText: He won first prize in the woodwind section.

data.chText: 一下子就能猜出她和谁在一起了。
data.enText: There are no prizes for guessing (= it is very easy to guess) who she was with.

data.chText: 抽中我们大奖的，得一辆汽车！
data.enText: Win a car in our grand prize draw !

data.chText: 难能可贵的事物；难以争取的重要事物
data.enText: something very important or valuable that is difficult to achieve or obtain

data.chText: 世界和平是最可贵的珍宝。
data.enText: World peace is the greatest prize of all.

data.chText: 好得足以得奖的；应获奖的

before.enText: especially of an animal, a flower or a vegetable

data.enText: good enough to win a prize in a competition

data.chText: 优秀的；典范性的；出类拔萃的
data.enText: being a very good example of its kind
He's a prize specimen of the human race!
She's a prize idiot (= very silly) .

data.chText: 尊诚实为美德之首的时代
data.enText: an era when honesty was prized above all other virtues

data.chText: 雪松油可用于制香水，因此十分珍贵。
data.enText: Oil of cedarwood is highly prized for its use in perfumery.

tr: something given as a token of victory
something given for victory or superiority in a contest or competition or for winning a lottery
example: the prize was a free trip to Europe

tr: to move or force, especially in an effort to get something open
example: The burglar jimmied the lock": "Raccoons managed to pry the lid off the garbage pail

value.boxr_value: The spelling prise is also used in British English for meanings 5 and 6. 在英国英语中，义项5和6亦可拼作prise。

value.def: A prize is money or something valuable that is given to someone who has the best results in a competition or game, or as a reward for doing good work.

example.ex: You must claim your prize by telephoning our claims line...
example.tran: 您必须通过拨打我们的领奖电话来领取奖品。

example.ex: He won first prize at the Leeds Piano Competition...
example.tran: 他在利兹国际钢琴比赛中荣获一等奖。

example.ex: He was awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1985...
example.tran: 他于1985年被授予诺贝尔物理学奖。

example.ex: They were going all out for the prize-money, £6,500 for the winning team.
example.tran: 他们正全力争取队伍获胜，以赢得6,500英镑的奖金。

value.def: You use prize to describe things that are of such good quality that they win prizes or deserve to win prizes.
You can refer to someone or something as a prize when people consider them to be of great value or importance.

example.ex: With no lands of his own, he was no great matrimonial prize.
example.tran: 他没有自己的地产，不是结婚的上佳人选。

value.tran: 非常珍贵的人（或物）；十分重要的人（或物）

value.def: Something that is prized is wanted and admired because it is considered to be very valuable or very good quality.

example.ex: Military figures, made out of lead are prized by collectors...
example.tran: 收藏家们对铅铸的军人塑像视若珍宝。

example.ex: One of the gallery's most prized possessions is the portrait of Ginevra de'Benci.
example.tran: 这个美术馆最珍贵的藏品之一是达芬奇的《女子肖像》。

value.def: If you prize something open or prize it away from a surface, you force it to open or force it to come away from the surface.

example.ex: He tried to prize the dog's mouth open...
example.tran: 他试图把这条狗的嘴掰开。

example.ex: I prised off the metal rim surrounding one of the dials...
example.tran: 我把其中一个刻度盘的金属边撬开了。

example.ex: He held on tight but she prised it from his fingers.
example.tran: 他抓得很紧，但她还是掰开他的手，把它拿走了。

value.boxr_value: in AM, usually use 美国英语通常用 pry

value.def: If you prize something such as information out of someone, you persuade them to tell you although they may be very unwilling to.

example.ex: Alison and I had to prize conversation out of him.
example.tran: 我和艾莉森只得从他口中撬出谈话内容。

value.tran: 竭力打探（消息等）；说服…透露（消息）

value.boxr_value: in AM, usually use 美国英语通常用 pry
